The dataset consists of 183412 bike riding records over 16 different informations of a bike sharing serive by Ford. Let's dive into it !

Introduction¶

The Bay Area's bike share scheme is Ford GoBike. Bay Area Bike Share was launched in 2013 as a regional test program, with 700 bikes and 70 stations spread between San Francisco and San Jose. Ford GoBike will have 7,000 bikes throughout San Francisco, the East Bay, and San Jose after the expansion is complete.

Ford GoBike, like other bike sharing systems, is made up of a fleet of specifically built, strong, and durable bikes that are docked at a network of docking stations located around the city. The bikes may be unlocked at any station in the system and returned to any other station, making them perfect for one-way excursions. People use bike sharing to travel to work or school, to conduct errands, to get to appointments or social events, and for other purposes. It's a fun, easy, and inexpensive way to go about.

The bikes are accessible for use 24 hours a day, seven days a week, 365 days a year, and riders who become members or purchase passes have access to all bikes in the network. The data may be found here. https://www.fordgobike.com/system-data

Dataset Overview¶¶

The dataset used in this research comes from the Ford GoBike sharing system in the wider San Francisco Bay region in 2019. (February). Wikipedia has a page dedicated to Bay Wheels. It is made up of different riding features as well as rider attributes.

The following characteristics from the cleaned dataset were investigated:

  • Duration of the journey (seconds)
  • Start Day
  • Start Time
  • Type of User ("Subscriber" = Member or "Customer" = Casual)
  • Age of the Member
  • Gender of the Member

Hourly usage of the Ford Go Bike System¶

In [37]:
# Hourly usage of the Ford Go Bike System
graph = sb.catplot(data = df_clean, x='start_time_hour', kind='count', color = no_color, aspect = 1.7)

graph.set_axis_labels('Hours', 'Number of Bike Rides')

graph.fig.suptitle('Ford GoBike System Usage by Hour', y=1.05, fontsize=16, fontweight='bold');

Observation 1¶

The bikes were most frequently used between the hours of 8-9 a.m. and 5-6 p.m., which corresponds to a normal workday in the United States. This lends credence to the notion that the bikes are mostly utilized by commuters.

Weekday usage of the Ford Go bike system¶

Observation 2¶

Tuesdays and Thursday appear to be the most popular days for utilizing the bike sharing system, while Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays are quite close. The utilization reduces considerably on Saturdays and Sundays, indicating that the Ford bike sharing system is mostly utilized for commuting during working days.

plt.xlabel('Duration (Min)')
plt.xticks(ticks, labels)
plt.ylabel('Number of Bike Trips');

Observation 3:¶

The average journey lasts slightly under 12.5 minutes, with 75% of visits lasting less than 14 minutes. According to the histogram, most trips last between 3 and 11 minutes. This implies that riders are only traveling short distances on their bikes.

Distribution of Age¶¶

In [49]:

Observation 5:¶

The average user's age is 35.5 years old. As a reminder, all users under the age of 65 were deleted from this data set during the cleaning process. According to the histogram, the bulk of users are between the ages of 25 and 40, which is also the age range of working individuals.

In general:¶

  • we have more male bikers than females
  • more subscribers than customers
  • practically no people who share trips
  • our maximum density from the ages of 24 to 36.
  • Females have longer duration rides than Males.
  • Males have older people biking than Females
  • Males and Females prefer the same time to take their rides, most of them prefer it at noon or a little after that
  • We have more Female customers than Males and almost the same percentage of Subscribers
  • Males and Females appear to prefer the same Staions.
  • Not all Staions have the same distributions, This also applies to Start and End Stations.
